title: LockDock
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
Keep your iDevice charger and cord right where you want it with LockDock. Secure the Apple® USB charger and charging cord to the wall socket and rest your device on top while it's plugged in.

Use it at home to keep your kids/roommates/parent from hiding your charger. Use it at work to keep your charger from wandering!
I got a call from someone with a need to secure their charger and cord, and a few days later I had this designed and ready to ship!

author: aclymer

description.text: I was trying to get my extruder speed dialed in and needed a single-walled test piece. Some great info on extruder speeds at http://rapmanv3.blogspot.com/2009/09/more-skienforge.html

The walls are .6mm .5mm .4mm and .3mm.
With standard .5mm nozzle and default skeinforge settings, all walls should be printed at the same speed/thickness. (I wanted the different sizes for calibrating a .35mm nozzle.)

title: Mounting for Samsung Galaxy Nexus
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This is intended to be used as a cradle for the phone to go with my car dock. I published the mounting plate I'm using as a separate thing here http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:15432. This model just has a blank section on the back to attach a mounting bracket for whatever stand you want to use. It's intended for a 40x40 mm square block to be attached there. It can be a bit taller but the width is already pretty tight. Note that I'm sizing this to fit my phone inside of the plastic case that was included for free when I bought it. It's a pretty thin case so it should fit without the case but you may want to consider some foam, rubber or other type of material to account for the extra size. I had to cancel my initial test print before it was done. It came out "done enough" so it seems unlikely I will ever make a full print out of it as intended. I was mostly finished designing this on paper when I noticed Seanz0rzâ€™ similar (and we can all admit nicer looking) thing seen here http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:14620. His is too small for my Galaxy Nexus so I finished this up. I made some changes to this based on his work so credit to him. This ended up beefier then it needs to be but I'm satisfied with it. Considering the 2-3 hour print time and the 'good enough' status I don't plan to revise this for at least a long while. I would suggest the following changes if any one else wants to revise it in the mean time:
  • Shrink the top clamp horizontally as it partially covers the power button.
  • Reduce the height of the main piece. Mine came out pretty good and is truncated in height.
  • Add cutouts to reduce plastic. Especially one to uncover the volume button.
  • Enlarge the screw head cutouts to fit washers
  • Additional mounting plates for common existing car docks
    • Update 1/18/12
    I've uploaded a slightly modified set of design files labeled v1.2/v2.2. These include some slight changes and are modified to hold a larger case.

Make a 40x40 square with the mounting for whatever your going to attach this to (see my example above).  Snap this into the back of the larger piece.  Mine snapped in tightly but I melted them together anyway.  
Use 4-40 or similar sized machine screws (hole printed at 4mm diameter but needs to be loose enough to slide) to mount the sliding top to the bottom.  They need to be about 3/4 in long.  I filled the screw head cutouts with epoxy so I don't have to prevent them from spinning while tightening the nuts.
Skeinforge added extra supports to the top piece since I forgot to turn them off.  Didn't seem worth printing again to test the built in support.

My road bike is sorely lacking in good locations to mount a rear light, but I ride in the dark a fair amount. I have an Ortlieb bar bag that I've relocated to a T Bar attached to the seat post, and I realized that it has a couple of snap connectors that I could use. They're intended for attaching a map pocket.
I don't know how durable this will be, it's an experiment. The snaps seem to be pretty positively locking, but probably if you snapped them in and out a lot they would wear out quickly. Since I plan to just snap it in place and leave it there, I hope this will last.

The snaps are 5mm farther apart than the measured distance on the bag. After printing, use a heat gun to soften a strip about 1/3 of the way along, then put in a twist that will bring the center bit out and vertical when snapped onto the bag.  Hold a few seconds while the plastic cools.  Repeat 1/3 of the way from the other side. Clip on the light using the strap clip (if your light didn't come with one, you'll have to improvise).

description.text:
I made this to try out a method to calibrate the extruder multiplier. I used the method in this video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=N-7uX6Dw-7A

This method really cleaned my prints up. It is an automated way for you to find the sweet spot for the extruder multiplier and filament temperature for each filament you are using.

Before you get to this step, I suggest you do the following:

First, I would make sure your stepper drivers are tuned to the correct voltage for the motor being driven. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=89BHS9hfSUk

Next, I would calibrate your extruder. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YUPfBJz3I6Y

Pi Zero case. Customisable design with OpenSCAD.

Uses 4 M2.5 8mm screws to hold together and make it easier to assemble / disassemble.

Height of lid part can be varied in OPENSCAD by changing lid_height ti provide extra space.

Updated to support latest PiZero with camera connector. This needed a little bit more length.

There is now a camera parameter in the OpenSCAD file which allows for an external camera (slot for cable access), an internal camera mount with a deeper lid, and the original lid with GPIO access. 3 v3 STLs give these variations.

21May Small tweak to internal camera holes to get better alignment. Also added a camera_screw_centre_offset to the scad. Nominally 0 for official cameras but I have found some third party cameras where holes were about 1mm off the centre of the lens.

5Jul V4 Added option to allow for right angle headers exiting sideways. THis makes it easy to mount a zero on a breadboard.

description.text:
This is a replacement shelf for a Frigidaire refrigerator shelf.
Model LFHT2117NF6.

This should also work on Magic Chef, Whirlpool and whatever else is in the family that uses this style of shelf..
You can look up my model number on the website and get the part number for the shelfs. You can then look up your model and see if the part number is the same..
I have included pictures of what the door looks like without the shelf in order to help. If yours looks like mine it will probably work.

All 3 of my shelves broke in less than a year so I came up with this sysem. It seems to work just fine.

The area that requires support is not visible when assembled so it is not bad to clean up.

Print in the orientation shown in the picture. use 3 outside layers.

The metal bar I used was purchased at Lowes. It measures 1"x 9/16".

For my fridge I cut the bar to lengths of 23 7/16" You want the bar as long as it can be before it gets tight to mount the shelf. Mine was the same length on all 3 shelves.

Then I drew all other details according to my measurements (taken with a caliper).
After I finished the design, I had to make a mirrored copy in Solidworks, so the new leg could fit in the proper spot (due to some hinges that are only on one side of the slot).

Bank shot! Blow some of the air behind the nozzle in the hopes of improving the surface finish on the far side of PLA parts.
Thanks to nhfoley for providing the source solidworks file on his excellent part.

Print both parts in ABS. PLA will melt. Clean up with a hobby knife and test fit. Trim the dovetail as necessary for a tight fit. Pre-drill the fan mounting holes M2.5 and form thread with an M3 screw. Assemble fans, fan covers and shroud and test fit. The tabs on the fan hanger should straddle the existing filament guide and may need to be trimmed to fit. Once you're happy with the fit around the nozzle, glue the two pieces together with super glue. Hold the parts in the right spot till the glue dries. Shroud clears the clips when aligned correctly.

description.text: This OpenSCAD library generates three different types of print-in-place hinges. All of the hinges can be printed fully assembled without support materials. One hinge type has a horizontal hinge axis, and the other two hinge types have vertical hinge axes. The hinge models are parameterized so that the size and clearances may be adjusted. In my experience, if there is a gap between adjacent hinge fingers when printing the first few layers, then the clearance parameter value is large enough. If you start printing and the hinge fingers overlap in the first layer, cancel the print and increase the hinge spacing value. The horizontal hinge design is inspired by http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:5922, but I wrote my version from scratch to give more control over the spacing and distribution of hinge arms. The two vertical hinges are my own designs. //UPDATED 11/8/13 - Added separate stl files for each example hinge type.
Download the OpenSCAD file and use it in your own designs.

title: 12mm Laser Bracket for FlashForge Creator Pro

description.text:
This is kind of a remix I think - I used the referenced "thing" to build the base sketch in Fusion360, but that sketch outline is all i used from their thing. The laser is a 12mm copper tube, and the heatsink for the laser is an Aixiz aluminum mount and heatsick for 12mm modules (AixiZ aluminum mount and heat sink for 12mm modules).

It puts the laser beam right down the gap between the existing heat sinks, and lets the laser heat sink contact the existing heat sinks to help a little more with cooling (I have a 7W laser diode, which is the reason for the larger fan and extra heat sink funciton.

Printer:

FlashForge Creator pro

No

Resolution:

2mm

100%

Notes:

Black ABS from Makerbot, 2mm layers, 4000mm/s on FF Creator Pro (1st layer 50% speed) with all metal hotend (0.4mm). Using 3 layers of 2 outline skirt, set 4mm from part (using Simplify3D)

Drill your holes

This is set up to drill your own holes for heat sink mounting and fan mounting to allow flexibility in fan selection and heat sink selection I recommend using a drill bit and screws that let it self tap for the heatsink. For the fan, you must self tap the holes unless you want to use 40mm long screws.

It also require that you drill out the space between the heat sinks with a 1/2" bit (which is 12.728-ish mm) for as far down as you want to focus ring to be able to go a half inch or so should be plenty. Then you can reach through the gap between the existing heat sicks with something narrow to adjust your laser focus without disassembling the whole thing.

description.text:
INTRODUCTION!!!!!!
If you are having problems with distortion in dimension in your print or your parts are not coming out in the correct proportion you may be in need to re-calibrate your axis in the x y or z axis. I designed this method for myself and it has worked very well as seen in the pictures. So, hopefully it will be much easier for other makers to make their printers have great dimensional accuracy utilizing this method.

THE METHOD?
1)Measure your nozzle extrusion of plastic with a caliper
2a)If you want to calibrate the z axis import in your slicer the z axis rectangle file along with the nozzle size
OR
2b)If you want to calibrate the x or y axis, import in your slicer the 60mm test box with accordance to your closest nozzle size.
3) Set your layer height to .2mm layers as these files are designed to utilize specifically this layer height.
4) Slice and print the file
5) Take off of print bed and measure the desired axis in question.
6) go into the excel document and input the desired measurements according to direction.
7) repeat 2 to 5 and determine if axis is within desired parameters if not then print again until axis is at your desired tolerances.

WHATS IN THE EXCEL DOCUMENT?
Excel document attached is utilized to make formulas for making estimates for steps and then the 3rd chart is utilized to refine your steps to get as close to 100% accuracy as possible.

HOW TO USE?
As seen, there are 20 some stl files to make your life easy. As 3d printer owners, all of us have different nozzle types for different applications. Stl files support .1mm to .6mm were you measure the output plastic from your nozzle or look at your firmware to determine which size wall to use from the stl files.

NOZZLE TYPES?
The end of the file names are the size of the nozzle the stl file is made for. EX) if you have a .46mm nozzle use the .45mm file!

DIMENSIONS FOR THE STL FILES
1) 60mm test box is 14mm high and 60mm in the x and y coordinates
2) The z axis rectangle test is 60mm high and 40mm in the x and y coordinates.

I hope this helps! Any way to improve on the method please let me know thank you!!!

NOTE 1/31/2012: We've updated the design by making the clamps a bit tighter. We found that the smooth rod grooves had a very tight tolerance and would not clamp the rods tight enough in some cases. This is a small update to the AO X-ends. The only major change is the bushing mount wall is beefed up good bit. The clamps are the same but have been uploaded here for ease of downloading the parts. Wanting to move away from the cast x-ends but also liking the clamp style, we designed some new ones to work with the boltable PLA bushings. These are interchangeable with the standard Prusa or cast Clonedel x-ends. This x-end set calls for a little extra hardware, but no glue and the ability to change out bushing easily makes up for it. Hardware:
x8 M3 20mm SHCS
x8 M3 12mm SHCS
x24 M3 washers
x16 M3 Nyloc nuts (or regular nuts)
For the idler
x1 M8 30mm SHCS
x1 M8 Nyloc
x2 M8 washers
x2 Fender washers
x1 608 bearing These x-ends use the boltable PLA bushings rather than the glue in PLA bushings. You can find the boltable bushings here: thingiverse.com/thing:10647. Also, we have made Igus bushings holder for these x-ends too: thingiverse.com/thing:13229 Licensing
-Parts and files: GPLv3
-Images: CC BY SA

You will need two clamps and one each of the idler and motor ends.
It is easier to bolt the PLA bushings onto the x-ends first with the 12mm screws and nuts. Then you can bolt the clamp on each end with the 20mm screws, but leave them loose. Once you put the x-end together you can tighten down the clamps. 
For the idler you will need to put the nut on the inside of the idler wall. There is not clearance to push the M8 bolt in from the inside of the wall.

description.text:
I wanted a carriage that allowed easy access to extruder wheel. I wanted the titan to face forward or to the left and I wanted to incorporate a cable chain mount for wire management.

I used Mike Kelly's carriage file as a starting point http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:647798

I included two cable chain mounts. They both fit this cable chain from amazon:
http://www.amazon.com/dp/B00880AVL2/ref=sr_ph_1?ie=UTF8&qid=1461680057&sr=sr-1&keywords=cable+chain

One is just the mount you can glue/stick whatever.

The second is attaced to a male gopro style clip mount. I used a go pro pad to attach to my case and the cable mount clips in easily.

A couple notes:

you will use ~22 links plus the ends for the cable chain if you mount near of case.

Carriage currently works for e3D V6 but would probably work fine with hex. May need to use alternate fan for heatsink as I did not leave mounting holes in place.

Current design is for 25mm pancake stepper motor (http://www.omc-stepperonline.com/nema-17-bipolar-step-motor-29v-07a-18ncm255ozin-17hs100704s-p-260.html). Will work with 20mm stepper as well. Will work with stock extruder stepper BUT you would lose 25mm of build area on your x-axis.

Using 25mm stepper you will lose about 10mm of build volume on the x-axis. I will be fixing this on my next revision.

Update - Remixed Novice Expert's toolless fan shroud to be a quick connect/disconnect as seen in pictures. updated fan shroud is available at http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1555114

title: Headlight Adjusting Knob
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
After replacing the headlights on my 2003 Expedition, I noticed that aligning them was a bit difficult because the size and location of the adjusting screw made it difficult to access with tools. I made two of these knobs to put on the shaft of the adjusting screw. The hex portion of the screw is very slightly under 4mm, so the knob is designed with a 4mm hex center. Due to the natural shrinkage, the end result fits perfectly snug and should stay in place.

I printed these in Ultimaker PLA, but ABS should work well also (you might need to scale it up ever so slightly with ABS if the fit is too snug due to the extra shrinkage).

description.text: In my boredom and spare time I have created a gameboy style controller. This is essentially a blank slate meaning that it has nothing in the manner of mounts for internals or cutouts for ports. It also doesnt have the grooves for buttons on the button cap since that may vary from person to person. This requires a little bit of extra modelling on the part of the people for your individual needs, but the majority of the work is done for you. Please upload your work as a remix of this so others can get to printing this a lot quicker. This is designed for m3 screws but a 3.5 might be required depending on the printer. You will also need to scale the button caps to 98% size when slicing or maybe even smaller depending on the printer. All buttons should stick out the same amount. Let me know how this prints for you, in the comments. Designed with TinkerCAD and OnShape, all modelling work done by me(yes even the pokemon logo)
This thing was made with Tinkercad. Edit it online https://www.tinkercad.com/things/1NgdZFy5y74

title: 3D Knot With Minimal Support -  Trinity Symbol

description.text:
This is my tweak on xorxo's "3D Knot (hi-res) with support".  HIs knot is great and prints very well too, but all the support it hard to remove and not necessary in many cases.  I trimmed down on the support material.  The square base and some base supports remain but not the original and often uneeded arch supports.  
I've always liked this shape with it being only one object and yet three pieces also, a good Trinity symbol.

Download -> Slice -> Print -> Enjoy!!.  ( I made this to be easy to print, and clean up.  The adhesive squre base can be easily torn off and th suppors easly clipped off with wire cutters.  A little sand paper or a file and your golden. :-)

comments.text: Great edit. What software do you use to alter STLs so precisely?
comments.author: fake_tissues

comments.text:
All the work is done in openscad, a free script based CAD system. In this case you open the
knot_large_less_support.scad file which is also dependent on the knot_hires.stl file. (thanks for asking the question - it caused me to notice the missing file in the file collection. :-) )
knot_large_less_support.scad opens the stl file and adds some basic geometric shapes to make the base and support parts. I'd highly recommend downloading and installing openscad. Its free and pretty friendly even though the idea of CAD design using scripts seems counterintuitive. Its actually extremely powerful once you get over the learning curve and there is a multitude of tutorials and examples out there to make learning it fun and easy. Its good cheap (free actually) nerdy fun. What more could you ask? :-)

description.text:
Proximity sensor mount for Greg's X-Carriage. You can use this to mount the 18mm diameter 6-36V proximity sensors to enable auto bed leveling.

I used this specific sensor and it worked great: Amazon Link

You can see it in action on my printer here: https://youtu.be/zFym7SAqkQk

To get this sensor to work you need to hook it up to +12 and ground, and use a voltage divider to keep from blowing up the input on the z endstop.

Two versions. One that uses the center mount point and one that leaves space for a capscrew. I did not have a screw long enough so omitting the center screw allowed me to use the existing screw for the extruder and the two unused mounts to hold the sensor in place.

title: Z Clamps for moving or shipping

description.text:
Added an update that has a flange and nut slot. This version can use a hex head bolt and a wing nut. So, no tools needed to loosed or tighten. We've had a few Z-couplers break during shipment so we made these clamps that hold the x-axis from moving. This file is actually just the new bar clamp from the Prusa iteration 2 with one hole made smaller for an M4 screw. Simple part for a simple job. Hardware:
x1 - M4 30mm SHCS
x2 - M4 washer
x1 - M4 nut

Snap the clamps onto the smooth rod above and below both x-ends. Put a screw and washer though, then washer and nut on the other side. Tighten all of the clamps nice and tight so they are touching the top and bottom of the x-ends.

title: Bowden setup for E3D Hotend on Prusa I2

description.text: This is a Bowden extruder setup for a Prusa I2 using the E3D hotend. These are just adaptors mounts. The extruder mount is used in conjunction with your existing Wades or Gregs hinged extrude and mounts to the two top horizontal threaded rods just outside of one of the Z axis motors. The E3D Large mount can be used in conjunction with your existing X carriage and mounts using the standard hotend mounting holes. The E3D Large mount has the fan shroud built in and mounting holes for the fan that comes with the E3D hotend. It has been designed to mount the majority of the hotend above the X carriage to maximize z travel.
For all three parts I used a .2mm layer height with a 33% infill

remixed_from.title: Wanhao Duplicator I3 Z brace with adjustable feet (Hardware store special)

title: SWD1 KIT Z-AXIS FOR WANHAO DUPLICATOR I3 / MONOPRICE MAKER SELECT
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This is a Remix on two separate designs found here on Thingiverse that inspired me.
First inspiration from the basic concept of AzzA's thick printed blocks.
I modeled in Inventor a complete revision of the front and Top connectors that extend out to make the rods parallel to the y axis.
Second inspiration was from TyphonPS's design with levelers.
The Mid feet and Rear Feet are redesigns on the concept by TyphonPS, that incorporates levelers in the bases of the yaxis blocks and the zaxis towers.

While only some similarities exist between both of the other two creations, these parts are completely rebuilt in inventor and checked against the Wanhao I3 Duplicator as to fit.

The Front and Rear Y axis braces that run along the front plate can be used from AzzA's kit as I have not recreated those parts for my own design as of yet but will be in the future with modifications to support changes on the Wanhao.

This Z axis mod was designed to eliminate the need to completely remove the Top Z-Axis bolts which could lead to getting the z-axis top frame out of square and causing issues for new Installers. By using the top 2 screw brace it allows a new unskilled modder to install the z-axis brace without completely disassembling the machine.

Additional Parts Needed

2) 5/16 Threaded Rod @ 375mm long
or 8mm Threaded Rod @ 375mm long

4) 5/16 Nylock Nuts - Replace with 8mm Nuts if using 8mm Rod
4) 5/16 Standard Nuts

26)M3 x 10mm Socket Cap Screws

6) 1/4-20 nuts
6) 1/4-20 Elevator bolts 1" long

6) 1" Dia x 1/8th thick Rubber pads (added to bottom of elevator bolts)

Installation process.

  1. Ensure Threaded rods are between 370mm and 380mm in lengths.

  2. Remove 3) M3x5 screws on front of y axis on one side, Mount New Bracket and replace with 3) M3x10mm and on the inside of the Y install 1) M3 x 10mm on Internal Brace. Repeat for opposite side. Then repeat for rear blocks minus the internal screw.

  3. Remove 2) M3 x5mm screws on the bottom of each z-axis tower and install the center feet with 2) M3x10mm screws each ctr foot.

  4. Install 6) 1/4-20 nuts in the blocks for the elevator bolts, then install 6 Elevator bolts

  5. Install threaded rods in the two front base blocks, 5/16 Nylocks run up before inserting into base and install 5/16 nut in base tube and thread rod into 5/16 nut. Slide printed cover over 5/16 nylock nut and slide an additional printed cover inverted next. Then Thread a standard 5/16 nut to fit in 2nd cap. Finally Install top z axis sleeve on threaded rod and cap off with 5/16 Nylock flush with end of threaded rod.

  6. Install the top z axis sleeve to the bottom two screws on the top z axis tower connector screws. Adjust and level Machine accordingly.

Printer:

Wanhao Duplicator i3 Monoprice Maker Select Wanhao Duplicator i3 Wanhao Duplicator i3 V1 Wanhao Duplicator i3 V2 Wanhao Duplicator i3 V2.1 Monoprice Maker Select IIIP 3D Printer Balco 3D Printer Cocoon Create 3D Printer Malyan M150 3D Printer Forge 3

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Doesn't Matter

Resolution:

.2mm thick layers

Infill:

30%

Notes:

Printed on Wanhao I3 Duplicator with the following mods.
Thumbwheel
Azza -Zaxis Mod
Basic Wanhao Built Tac Bed
No other mods on printer.

.2mm layers
1.75mm Retraction Distance
35mm Retraction speed

1.2mm thick shells /top/bottom layers

50mm/sec infill speed
30mm/sec outer shell speed
45mm/sec inner shell speed

15% infil overlap

This was based on two different existing Mods on Thingiverse

This was designed with the new Wanhao/Cocoon Create/Maker Select/ Maylan M150 users in mind. I saw a need for the new machines to not be completely disassembled just to add a very important mod that stabilizes the machines.

This was done by incorporating a 2pc top brace piece and an extended front base to allow the z-axis rods to run parallel while not exerting multiple angular forces on the y-axis and stabilizing the vertical z-axis.

Additionally with the use of the levelers and the rods being parallel to the y-axis the machine is extremely stable. This has been installed on my machine for more than a month and I have practically eliminated all ringing due to the stability.

The attached .stl files were created completely from New .IPT files in Autodesk Inventor 2014.

The primary nylock Nut needs to be run up as shown before sliding into the hex tube.

comments.text: You need to make sure your bed and rails are square. The brace is on there to stabilize the z axis to keep it from vibrating and causing issues with the prints. When you added the 4 corners if you did not keep the rails and the bed level it could now be twisted slightly. There are tutorials on the Wanhao users group on how to blueprint your machine to make sure everything is square and level. There is also a Wiki site but currently I am at work and cannot get to a link. Hope that helps and good luck.

comments.text: Can someone re-explain how to install the rods and nuts? I can't quite figure it out.
comments.author: cschaaf

comments.text:
I have not had the chance to create the .pdf but here is the way I did it.
1 take the 5/16 rod and run the nylock nut on to the rod let the threaded part of the rod stick past the rounded part of the nylock approximately the same as the thickness of the nylock nut.
2 take the assembled rod and push it through from the bottom of the bottom foot but only half way.
3 thread first standard nut down to base from the top
4 install nut cap down to the first nut.
5 install 2nc nut cap inverted to the first one so that it will cover the next nut.
6 thread second standard nut down approximately 3" from top edge of threaded rod.
7 Slide the threaded rod up until the nylock nut seats in the tube and the top of the threaded rod protrudes out of the top of the top z-bracket.
8 thread either a standard 5/16 nut or a 2nd nylock Nut on the top end of the threaded rod.
9 tighten the lower most standard nut down until the nylock and the standard nut are both tight.
10 repeat for the other side
11 Use the top two nuts to adjust the z-squareness without adjusting the bottom two.
Hope that helps until I can get the .pdf and video out.

Not knowing which slicer you are using and or what state your printer is in as far as accuracy a simple option if you used 3 outline walls would be to use a drill bit the side of your threaded rod and clean out the hole. This is a simple fix as apposed to several hours of upscaling and reprinting the parts. Key question here is will the nuts fit into the feet. If the nuts do not fit at all you will have to reprint as apparently there is a accuracy issue with your printer.
Let me know how it goes :)

Since then I reset the models to be the exact size needed at a .3mm oversize on each of the holes. Take care and happy printing.

comments.text:
The design is set to stabilize the z axis frame and to make it perpendicular to the y axis frame.
First I would level the y axis with the 4 leveling feet.
Once the y axis is level then I would loosen on each side one of the screws that attach the z axis to the y axis.
With the y axis level I would use a 90 degree metal square and align the z-axis 90 degrees to the y axis.
At this point then tighten the rods into place to keep the z axis perpendicular to the y axis.
Short list:
Level y axis
Set z axis to 90 degrees of Y axis
tighten rods to maintain 90 degrees.
tighten any other loosened screws.

comments.text: after watching the video I noticed that you had raft at the top of the z axis cap nut, If you flip those over in your slicer you will not need a raft and the round section in the center is a manual modeled support for the opening at the top. I should have made several different nut caps with different nub sizes just ran out of time. if you flip those over and remove the center section after they print they should work fine. Additionally take a look at the orientation of your parts when they print when I created these I typically printed things in sets like the front feet were in pairs facing eachother and the same for the rear feet. I was able to print all the pcs on one bed load but I left them loose for people to arrange on their printer as they saw fit. Hope that helps and if you have any questions just let me know.

description.text:
Ce châssis est une version Beta pour un quadcopter à base carrée de 250mm de diagonale. Il est prévu pour accueillir des moteur brushless 1806 (4 vis) et 2204 (2 vis) (2300kv en 3S pour ma part).
l'espacement prévu pour la carte de vol est de 30.5mm, compatible CC3D et Naze 32.

pour les renforts de bras, prévoir du tube carbone 6mm (on en trouve facilement sur des flèches d'arc en magasin de sport), j'ai utilisé personnellement du tube en fibre de verre trouvé au rayon cerf-volant.

Ma version est imprimée en NGen (équivalent de l'ABS proposer par ColorFabb) qui a la particularité d'être léger, assez souple et imprimable sans plateau chauffant (prévoir un peu de brim)

Ce châssis est prévu pour 8 vis M3 de 42mm de longueur (j'ai utilisé de la tige filetée coupée et limée) et des entretoises M3 (j'ai utilisé des entretoises nylon pour espacer les cartes de vol et carte d'alimentation du chassis)

J'ai placé de la bande velcro découpée sur la plaque du dessus pour placer batterie et récepteur 2.4GHz.

Il à été dessiné sur FreeCAD (version 0.15) et les fichiers sont disponibles et modifiable à volonté. Il manque encore à ce châssis un support de camera (sinon prévoir du ruban adhésif)

This is a beta version of a quadcopter, with a square base of 250mm.
It's compatible with 2204 (2 screw) and 1806 (4 screw) brushless motors (I used 2300Kv 3s 1806)

For arm reinforcements, you can use 6mm carbon tube (such as arrow shafts from a sports shop) or 6mm glass fiber kite arms.

My version was printed with NGen (ABS equivalent supplied by ColorFabb). It's light, flexible and easily printed without a heating bed (provide a bit of brim).

The frame is designed for M3 screws of 42mm in length (I used threaded rod, cut and filed to size) and M3 spacers (nylon spacers, in my case, for both the flight controller and power supply).

I stuck adhesive velcro on the top, cut and adjusted, so as to attach the LiPo battery and radio receiver.

It's drawn with FreeCAD 0.15 and the files are freely available for modification. A camera support has not been designed yet (you can always use gaffer-tape!).

description.text:
These are traffic cones printable in six pieces. I printed mine in black, white and orange. It could be printed in one color and painted if necessary.  
Each piece is designed to slot neatly on each other, though glue of some kind will be required to hold them together.  
This is a complete remodel of thing 49702, making for a much simpler model that stacks nicely.  
These are scaled to 1:6 at 28 inches tall to scale with 12" Action Figures like GI Joe or Dragon figures.  
The Gradated one is more standard than the original. I rarely see any that are evenly spaced between white and orange.  
The same base can be used for both.  
I pushed up files to print the orange segments and the white segments concentrically in one print, nested inside each other, not touching.  
If that isn't useful for your particular printer, I have included each segment separately.

comments.text: There are two cones in the file list. The "Gradated" one is the more standard cone, with different size stripes. You print each piece in the color specified in the file. The other set is a non-gradated version where the stripes are the same vertical height. You can also print the two "28 inch" files, which contain the striped pieces concentrically arranged so they all print in one go each.

text = Justin
Es una llanta o rueda para el moto reductor genérico, como el de la fotografía que se muestra.

I printed the cannon by Zheng3 and decided I wanted to make a few improvements. This one is slightly larger although has the same bore diameter. One of the main improvements I made was that I made the breach cap threaded and also threaded the end of the barrel so it is easier to attach the cap. Maybe this will also make it stronger but not sure. I also added a couple more supports between the frames including one at the top to make it slightly more rigid, the cannon barrel also fits a bit tighter. I also made the fuse hole come out at an angle to make it slightly easier to feed the fuse through.

Attached you will find the Openscad file in case you want to modify further as well as 3 printable files. There is a file with all parts as well as a file for just the 2 frame halves and a file for just the barrel/cap. I printed mine with the infill set to 50% on the frame but 100% on the barrel/cap and is the reason I broke them up, not to mention the barrel/cap will likely be worn out before the frame.

I may make more improvements after some testing. I am hoping it will withstand a Black Cat firecracker but we will see. What type of firecrackers have others tried in the original?

UPDATE 5/11: I have updated the cannon barrel and cap based on feedback from a user who tested the cannon (thanks @mikel0142 ). The threads on the barrel and cap have been reversed and I have also added some vent holes in the cap to hopefully help relieve some pressure and avoid the cap threads tearing apart. If this does still happen I expect that only the cap would be damaged now and could be quickly re-printed. I have also split each part into separate files so that you can print only a single piece if needed. I have printed everything but have not been able to test fire it so any feedback is welcome.

Printer:

FlashForge Creator Pro

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

No

Resolution:

.2 mm

Infill:

50%/100%

Notes:

barrel/cap = 100% infill (Recommend so that the barrel/cap do not explode)
frame = 50% infill (feel free to experiment here)

Assembly

Place the cannon barrel between the 2 frame halves with the fuse hole facing upwards and fit the 2 halves together, some glue in each hole on the left side of frame will help hold it together. It can be a pain to keep the barrel lined up while pressing the halves together but with a little patience you will get it. The cap is screwed into the back of the barrel before firing.

description.text:
Your standard issue Menger sponges! I was inspired by this video from standupmaths to see how easy it was to draw up. Attached are the resulting .STLs for a level 0 (no holes) through 4 (316 holes per face) sponge. I managed to piece together a level 5 sponge STL with Solidworks, which you can find here on GrabCAD.

First upload and time on this site, hope this all works properly.

Some Details

I originally drew these in (and indeed the .STL uploads were exported from) Solidworks, but just for you guys I figured out how to reproduce it in OpenSCAD as well, and am actually pretty impressed at how elegant the code ended up. As far as I've been able to test on my own computer OpenSCAD can't render higher than level 4 (F6 on the level 4 sponge took about 9 hours to finish rendering), but theoretically the function I built in should mathematically work for arbitrary recursion depths. I don't know enough about how the software or computer memory/processing in general work to say how hard it would be to go further.

The geometry actually gets large and complicated very quickly, what with all the holes in each direction crossing each other. As a result, the level 5 sponge that I managed to create after hours of tinkering and export/reimporting and body combination in Solidworks results in a .STL with about 10 million triangles that is almost 500MB and too big too upload here. Apparently not a problem over at GrabCAD though.

Printed on a Makerbot Replicator 2, but since they're in my school's maker space I didn't have a ton of liberty to tinker with settings or orientation or, pretty significantly, support structure.

My level 4 print Solidworks put up a fight

title: 12mm Y rod mounting hardware for the Lulzbot Taz 6 printer

description.text:
I thought the Taz 6 had 12mm Y rails in the stock configuration. It turns out that it doesn't. So, this project aims to create a set. This replaces the existing stock 10mm rods wiht 12mm rods. You should consider the http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:949082 Openbuilds V slot Y axis for Taz project as a better alternative to this one, but this implementation should be less expensive.

You will need:
The stock Taz 6 hardware including the flexi feet
28 M3 heat set inserts.
4 M5 heat set inserts
The 4 corner pieces (2 left, two right, front to back are identical on opposite corners)
4 of the retrofit 12mm bed bearing holders
4 LM12UU (sp?) bearings, whatever the one in the Taz 12mm Single bearing holder on the carriage is
2 500mm long 12mm rods (preferably hardened)

Printer Brand:

LulzBot

Printer:

TAZ 5

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.50mm nozzle

Infill:

85% or better

Notes:

The bed mounts in particular should probably be ABS or similar thermoplastic. The corners can be other materials.

Instructions
  1. Print out all of the pieces
  2. Insert the heat set inserts into all of the pieces. Each of the bearing mount units recieve 4 M3 inserts, the corner pieces each recieve one M3 at the top for the rod mount, and one M5 for the front plate mount.
    One other insert goes in the foot hole. I'm not sure if it's an M3 or an M5 though.
  3. Remove the existing hardware 1 side at a time, and replace with the new 12mm hardware.
    The automatic bed leveling should compensate for any change in height. You may lose 1mm wiht this design total Z travel. A future revision may move that bearing down a bit if it looks to be an issue long term.

Happy Printing, let me know if it needs any tweaks!

comments.text: Hello, does it fit on a TAZ 5 ?
comments.author: MarcElbichon

comments.text: Yes, you could also use this with a Taz 5. You would need to source the flexy feet or substitute some other form of mounting feet, and you would need to modify the bushing mounts as the taz 6 bed bolt pattern is slightly different, or drill the bolt holes out on the Taz 5 bed. Another option would be fit a Taz 6 bed plate, which you can source from itworks3d.com

description.text:
UPDATE - 5/15/16

I've redesigned the files, but my printer has been busy all weekend printing the Quin doll my granddaughter has requested, so the new files are definitely beta at this point because I haven't been able to test them yet. Hopefully the updated pot portion will print without supports now, and the bottom part will fit without falling through but without being too snug. I'm leaving the original files as well, because I'd still like to do some more testing to see if it's possible to keep the PLA-only wick working with lower water levels. (I'll post new photos once I've regained autonomous control of my printer!)

Description:

I'm really bad at starting seeds, because I get distracted and forget to water/mist them frequently enough to keep the seedlings alive. I'm hoping this will change that for me. It's probably not a practical tool for avid gardeners with massive quantities of seeds to start, but then again, those sorts of people probably don't forget to water theirs, anyway. :)

It's sized to fit into a pint-sized widemouth Mason jar, and you can just set it in for easy filling, or screw it down with a ring cap if you prefer.

To assemble, drop the pot portion into the top of a Mason jar, fill the jar with water up to the bottom of the pot (to get the wicking action going), then drop the bottom part through the hole in the bottom of the pot before adding soil and seeds. Make sure to press the soil in firmly enough so that it makes solid contact with the top of the wick, so the water will continue to be drawn up even after the level drops below the bottom of the pot.

If you're using the string version, before assembly cut 2-4 lengths of string approximately twice the depth of the jar. Fold each length in half and feed it up through the tube in the center of the bottom piece, push it through one of the holes, place the loop around the little hook next to the hole, and pull it snug to keep it in place. (See comments for some recommendations on types of string/yarn to use.)

If you're using the soil version, print the wick portion from PLA using a thin (1mm or less) outer shell, fill it, with your planting medium and use a pencil, dowel, etc. to eliminate any air pockets. (It may turn out this part needs to have a few small holes in it to let in enough water, but PLA isn't water-tight so it may be fine without them.)

When you're ready to plant the seedlings you can push the bottom piece upward to pop the soil and seedlings out for planting, to keep from disturbing the roots too much.

Print Settings for Updated Versions

Use PLA for the soil wick. Other than that, filament type isn't important -- use what you like. Everything should now print without supports, and shouldn't need much (if any) infill.

Original version:

My thought was that because PLA isn't water-tight, it might be possible to make it work as a wick, using the infill pattern to act as a wick to draw water up from the jar into the soil in the pot, and keep the seeds / seedlings watered. My first experimental sets using 50% and 40% infill stayed damp until the water level got too far below the bottom of the pot, and then stopped wicking, so either I haven't found the ideal infill percentage, or the idea just isn't viable.

To try it for yourself, pick an infill percentage you think will allow large enough pores to overcome surface tension and small enough to minimize gravitational pull (I haven't found the magic size, yet!). You also need to turn off the options for solid infill on the top and bottom layers, so the water can get into the wick part to begin with. If you use Cura, you can find that option in the Expert Settings screen.

author: lmc590

description.text:
A spiral! Modeled after one of those wooden spirals that hang on the ceiling, but hollowed to save plastic and colored as desired! Make it as long as you like, set the curve, rearrange, and enjoy!  
If you make one, please post a picture!  
It's only a work in progress in that I may add a few things to it such as a hole for string to hang it.

Just a few things to point out. Print this with 1 shell because more than that will make the connection too snug and you will need a hammer and/or wd-40 to use it properly. The other thing to consider is curling or deformation. I experienced both of those things, printing 5 to a plate, but in the end it's not really noticeable here.

comments.text: I printed the remix, but my printer needs adjustment....severe curling. I uploaded some pictures of the LED installation. It looks promising.
comments.author: janbeckman

comments.text: I remixed it a bit to make it possible to mount some LED tape into the spiral. The remix is here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:155366http://www.thingiverse.com/thi.... The tape I used was 8mm wide, 60 LEDs/meter. Available on http://DX.comDX.com. Just two little strips of 5 cm long on each side of the center. The electrical supply (12v) can be run down the center joint, two holes are provided in each "basket"
comments.author: janbeckman

title: Sprue a helper for small parts

description.text:
See install section for additional notes. Sprue 1 & 2 are nearly identical. 2 uses the new formula, so it is rotated correctly. 3 bypasses the problem I was having with Makerware. 4 is set so that if you scale down by a factor of 10, there should be only 1 layer. If you are like me, you print lots of small parts all at once. However, when one breaks away, you have to clear the plate, and start over. Sprue was designed as a type of rafting, that was meant not as a raft, but as a model sprue, from those old plastic models we used to build. So this does 2 things, connects the models together in an easy to dispose of format, and provide enough surface contact to keep your pieces down. If you are using openscad, here is the formula. y = 150; //Max Y mm
x = 260; //Max X mm
gapx = 10; //gap of x mm
gapy = 75; //gap of y mm
hscale = 10; //will scale down to 1mm.
vscale = 1; //will scale down to 0.01mm.
translate([-(xhscale)/2,-(yhscale)/2,0])
{
for (i = [0:gapxhscale:xhscale])
{
translate([i,0,0])
cube([1hscale,(y+1)hscale,1vscale]);
}
for (i = [0:gapyhscale:yhscale])
{
translate([0,i,0])
cube([(x +1)hscale,1hscale,1vscale]);
}
}As you can see, this is easy enough to modify. This has had the benefit of holding my struts in place when I do lots of rafting, So I am at a win-win here. Final Version Posted.

Makerware breaks up the model into hundreds of 10mm by 10mm squares. Don't do that. This works by having long continuous lines.  
You may need to generate the model in another tool to get it to work right.  
I will post those directions as soon as I can figure them out.  
Also note that This model needs to be rotated 90 degrees. I will fix that and repost.  
Do not merge this with your model, but print this first. Then your model on top of it. That seems to have the best effect.

title: Laser Cut Mason Jar Carry Case

description.text:
I do a lot of canning at home and I have a lot of mason jars. This helps carry them around to take to the office or to gift a few mason jars full of yum.

The lid is removable and the carry handle sticks through. There is a little room to spare inside each cell that can be used to add cardboard padding or napkins.

This uses 1/4" plywood and can be cut in 2 1x2 sheets. It assumes a nominal thickness of about 0.20". This SVG is the second revision and I hope to have one more.

The fingers are a bit long for 0.21" thickness. In the example I shaved off the tabs with a chisel. It is not required but it certainly made sanding and urethane easier!

author: Seb200

description.text:
Originally making this sine wave https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:20177, but I had trouble with the ball bearing using BBs, so I made a 3 part slew bearing one inspired from other design from this site.

The 2 inner parts bolt together, sandwiching the balls. The whole things rotates ok (but not nearly as good as real ball bearing). The whole assembly can't be separated once assembled.

It seems to glide well enough, but it could use some further work.

  • more clearance on BB track, for smoother BB movement
  • use 6mm BBs.
  • print outer parts in 2 halves (less overhang defects)

print_settings.Notes:: Piezas impresas en PLA

description.text:
ANTECEDENTES

La historia de este pequeño Printbot, del que estamos muy orgullosos, comienza hace unos meses, cuando mi hijo Javier de 8 años recibió como regalo de Reyes un kit de Robótica (de bq, os lo recomiendo) y empezamos a trastear con cosas de electronica básica, arduino y demás. Y teniendo una impresora 3D y despues de montar algún que otro printbot, dijimos, ¿Y por que no intentamos hacer uno nosotros desde cero? ¿Y si diseñamos uno y vemos si somos capaces?
He de decir, que nuestros conocimientos de electrónica, programación y automatismos era "0", y salvo el tema del diseño y modelado 3D, de lo cual algo controlo, todo lo demás estaba por hacer.

AGRADECIMIENTOS

Antes de seguir contando esto he de dar las gracias a la gente de bq, a su plataforma DIWO, a sus cursos de robótica y a su plataforma de programación por cajas de Arduino bitbloq.
Muy especialmente quiero agradecer a Juan Carlos, de PROMETEC (http://www.prometec.net) por su excelente curso abierto de Arduino, sin el cual hubiera sido imposible acometer esta tarea.
También he de dar las gracias a Javier Vidal Peña (https://Twitter.com/javidalpe) que con paciencia nos ha ayudado a hacer la web de control y a depurar nuestro código del programa.

EL CONCEPTO

La idea era hacer un robot por control remoto, con cámara integrada, para poder ser manejado a distancia y sin tener visión directa de él. De los posibles sistemas de control remoto se nos antojó como más adecuado el WIFI, ya que pensábamos que nos permitiría una mayor autonomía, cobertura y posibilidad de transmisión de vídeo en tiempo real, al menos en un área controlada, y con posibilidad de llegar a controlarlo en remoto desde internet (esta parte está aun por lograr).
Dado que teníamos una Gopro, la cual se conecta en streaming con su propia app con el teléfono móvil, pensamos que parte del trabajo ya lo teníamos solucionado, y todo lo que quedaba era resolver el control del movimiento del robot.
Un importante handicap que se nos presentó en las primeras pruebas, fue el descubir que el streaming de la cámara tiene un retardo de unos segundos. Este pequeño inconveniente, no obstante para nosotros tenía algo de positivo, o simpático ya que hacía que el control del robot se pareciese a manejar un robot en marte!!!!!! Seguramente será algo con solución, pero en nuestro caso, es casi mas un punto a favor que una pega.
Dicho esto, por lo demás se trata de un rover con dos servos de rotación continua, montados en un chasis sobre el que se sitúa la electrónica y una montura para la cámara, con un micro servo que permite el giro de 180º.

LAS PIEZAS IMPRESAS

Para el diseño de las piezas nos hemos servido de nuestra experiencia previa montando los printbots de bq (beaetle, y renacuajo) y alguno más que hemos visto aquí en thingiverse, Hemos partido de algunas piezas de ellos, las cuales hemos copiado i/o modificado para dar con nuestra solución. La idea ha sido construir un chasis solido, sencillo y compacto. Para su diseño hemos usado autcad y sketchup.
Hemos tenido algunos pequeños problemas de colisiones y por ello veréis que el robot está impreso en dos colores, pues ha sido necesario retocar algunas piezas del primer prototipo por problemas de encajes. Esto con un solidworks o un inventor no pasa!
Las que hemos subido en su versión actual son las del prototipo que veis impreso. Estamos trabajando en mejorar algunas cosas, como una montura para el wifi.

COMPONENTES PRINCIPALES

Placa controladora Freaduino UNO (compatible con arduino UNO, o similar. Esta tiene la ventaja de incorporar en la propia placa los conectores SVG en cada PIN)
2 Servos de Rotación Continua SM-S4303R o similares
Un micro servo de 9g (y sus tornillos)
Modulo WIFI ESP8266 (conector FTDI para programarlo si es necesario)
Una Cámara Gopro Hero 3, con su montura (O similar con WIFI)
Tornillos y tuercas M3 (distintas medidas, 12, 14, 30 mm, etc)
Una bola o canica o rodamiento de 12 mm de diámetro
2 juntas tóricas de 50 mm
Un portapilas 8 x AAA
Una miniprotoboard
Algunos cables de protoboard

FUNCIONES PRINCIPALES Y CONTROL

Avanzar, retroceder, giro a izquierdas, a Derechas y parada.
Movimiento de cámara a derecha, a izquierda y posición central.

Con la web de control se controla mediante pulsaciones en las flechas.
Hay que ejecutar mediante comandos AT en el monitor serie del Arduino lo siguiente:

AT+CIFSR? // Esto nos dara la URL de nuestro ESP8266
AT+CWLAP="tured","tucontraseña" //Esto solo una vez, ya que se queda almacenado.

En la web de control hay un cuadro a rellenar con la URL de tu printbot (la que has obtenido al ejecutar el comando AT+CIFSR?

Recomiendo echar un vistazo a los tutoriales del ESP 8266 de www.prometec.net, en donde se explica muy bien como configurar el ESP8266 y sus peculiaridades.
http://www.prometec.net/arduino-wifi/

He adjuntado el programa de control, aun en fase de depuración y mejora. Se admiten sugerencias y aportes (Esta es nuestra parte mas floja) ;) Y como digo, he puesto una versión Beta, a medio funcionar. Espero en unos días tenerla completa, correcta y más depurada. Lo pongo así, con la esperanza de que alguno que controle más nos eche una mano!

El fichero controlweb.html se ejecuta en el explorador para el control del printbot (mantener pulsada la flecha de movimiento, y soltar para detener).

Para Terminar, un par de videos de la fase de pruebas (en bucle y sin control WIFI). En breve pondremos videos del manejo en remoto:

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HMv9-_M3Ngg
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LGqeGaWIHyk

title: Fiio Olympus E10 Mount with Headphone Holder

description.text: This has flanges on both sides so you can mount it under your desk. It provides a nice and clean way to hide your Fiio Olympus E10, yet still make it accessible while also holding your headphones.

comments.text: FYI, another maker remixed this to a version without the headphone holder: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2216273

comments.text: This is perfect for me! Was looking for some holder for my headphones, and recently bought the E10. But how would you actually go about printing this? How would you orient it on the printing surface?
comments.author: mrath

comments.text: Hi there, when I printed this I printed it in the orientation in the second picture.  I usually try to print things with the exposed surfaces upwards so they end up cleaner looking.

author: Greenbird3

description.text:
This is a variation of the Void Cube that does not require colored sides.  Instead, each side has different sized edges and corners that distinguish them from the others.  It also makes for a pretty odd looking cube when it's scrambled (if you can still consider it a cube at that point)!  
The cube is larger by an added 15mm on each axis, so it is quite a bit larger than a regular cube.  
This version is actually a bit harder to twist because it's more difficult to get all of the pieces aligned perfectly, the pieces are just so oddly shaped.  Perhaps adding a little bit of rounding to the corners might make it easier.  That being said, the puzzle itself is much more difficult than a normal stickered cube because now you have to deal with varying sizes and orientations.  
Enjoy!
You'll need the inner edges and track rings from the original version, but instead of printing x copies of the original corner and edge pieces, you print one each of the pieces included here.

comments.text: this looks amazing. After inspecting the pieces it appears this could be doable, but would be my most intense print so far (i've had my printer for about a week). I will report back to say if it was successful. good job with making the parts printable (or what seems so). wish me luck! i freaking love the green color, if this works with the blue filament I have I will for sure do it again in green.
comments.author: jonnyb42

comments.text: Great to hear. Just be careful, the models have no tolerance in them, so if you print them as is they won't fit together. If you have a slicer that can adjust wall tolerance, you can use that to adjust their fit

comments.text: oh.... welp, that sucks. prints almost over and i adjusted nothing :D

title: Carbon skeleton Open RC rear wishbone

description.text:
Carbon skeleton or 3D component carbon fiber is technique where you print only mounting components of your part. Components are fixed in proper fixing structure and connected with carbon fiber tow.

You will create lightweight and rigid carbon fiber parts done by real continuous carbon fiber tow.

All details including test results can be found in my instructables tutorial, or briefly bellow.
http://www.instructables.com/id/Super-Strong-3D-Component-Carbon-Fiber-Parts/

Printer Brand:

Ultimaker

Printer:

Ultimaker 2

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Infill:

100

Notes:

Material ColorFabb - XT-CF20

1. fix parts in fixing structure 2. insert 1x3mm carbon profiles 3. Insert mounting points. 1,2mm carbon rods to wire carbon around. (picture from another part) 4. Wire tow all around the part, epoxy all fibers in every 2-6 turns. Wait for epoxy to cure and sand excess stuff 6. Cut excess, sand and use Troubleshoot: I had few problems with final part, i had to remove two carbon fiber bridges to be able to mount it. Also because if design of 3D printed shock the clearence with add cerabon fiber was to high so arm is not able to move in whole range. Prepare some winding ideas before to start with chaotic winding as me, it will help you to avit this problems.

1. Recreate mountin components of your part 1. Recreate mountin components of your part 2. Remove original part 3. expand it for mounting points and grooves for carbon tow 4. create mounting fixture (print it 2x) 5. Send to your slicer

Total weight is higher than part from ABS, but strength is much more higher also. Please find carbon quadcopter arms done by this way in my profile for bend tests. Sorry for forgotten screw :) ABS part have bug problems between layers for such thin and tall part to print, it breaks easilly

author: petrex

print_settings.Notes:: Material ColorFabb - XT-CF20

description.text:
Carbon skeleton or 3D component carbon fiber is technique where you print only mounting components of your part. Components are fixed in proper fixing structure and connected with carbon fiber tow.

You will create lightweight and rigid carbon fiber parts done by real continuous carbon fiber tow.

All details including test results can be found in my instructables tutorial, or briefly bellow. http://www.instructables.com/id/Super-Strong-3D-Component-Carbon-Fiber-Parts/

Printer Brand:

Ultimaker

Printer:

Ultimaker 2

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Infill:

100

Notes:

Material ColorFabb - XT-CF20

1. Glue in 1,2mm carbon rods as supports for carbon fiber winding. 2. Glue in 1x3mm profiles and fix it to fixing structure. let super glue to cure completely, it react with epoxy causing smoke and corrupting joints. 3. Connect end of fiber to fixing structure, it will help you to tighten fiber in first rows 4. mix the epoxy 5. Do the job. Put epoxy to all fibers every 4-6 rounds. Do X structures from sides and top. I put approximately 6m of 3K fiber to it. 6. Let it cure for min 24hours and sand remainings

print_settings.Notes:: It's necessary to steam the parts

description.text:
Für unterwegs, falls keine Toilette in der Nähe ist (oder die Toilette nicht dem entspricht, was man erwarten würde).
Die Schale hat einen Gewinde, das an alle PET Flaschen passen sollte. Somit hat man eine Hand frei und automatisch eine sichere Aufbewarungsmöglichkeit, bis man den Inhalt entsorgen kann.
Alternativ ist eine Verlängerung dabei, die man auch aufschrauben kann. Das ist zwingend, um eine ausreichenden "Reichweite" zu bekommen.
Zur Monatge, der Hauptteil besteht aus 2 Teilen, da mein Drucker zu klein ist. Die Teile kann man aber leicht mit dem Pattex "Special Kleber" kleben (oder eben mit Aceton). Zwingend ist, das ganze im Anschluss mit Aceton zu bedampfen.

author: Seb200

title: Big Brad 3D - some like it BIG!!! End of support

description.text:
October 2015 Ended up with selling this huge thing. Due to some more professional work no more time for it...Gained a lot of experience with this, I highly recommend to do this if you want to go further in this field...
  • Jan 2014
    Some new projects are calling...need space, and, of course money...
    I sell this working Big Brad as an experimental platform fully equipped with now Bowden Extruder, 700W heated printbed, just plug it in and print... all files of course
    29.Oct..Added video of working BigBrad after adding a heated glassbed...and my mistake, corrected dates here...I am always ahead of time....;-))
  • Oct. Added heated printed: 6 mm safety glass with two 360W het pads 220V switched by a solidstate relais. Fixed it with some selfmade clamps to the former print beds. Excellent results with 65 C, PLA sticks as hell. Now need some improvement on the z-axis due to the weight of the new parts...
    • 12.10
    New y-Carriage with plate for endstop mount and some enhancement in structure AddedAdded 11. Oct Redesign of extruder carriage due to some size issues, print it in ABS at 245 C to have a strong bond with raft & support. Also reworked Rod-Holder with pulley to make it stronger. Added 3. Oct. Redesign with parts in 3D more simpel setup less
    parts...
    Uploaded STL and Rhino files... If you start building one let me know Just finished my 3D printer...real BIG, gives you a print area of 46cm (x), 32 cm (y) and a height of 42 cm...can be tuned to some more cm because of quick design of parts...non-heated print beds, PLA sticks perfect with raft AND my wifeys hairspray (use lot of it..). No warping then... Powered by a standard RAMPS 1.4 , LCD Graphics with SD for standalaone print, chinese small NEMA17, (2x Y-Axis, 3x Z-Axis, 1 x-carriage, 1 extruder direct drive (thanks terenceang, http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:93695) ..., ATX-power-supply, 0,5 nozzle, 1,75mm filament, mechanical endstops. Some adjustments made to Marlin (thanks...) All parts are my own design, printed on a makerbot clone in PLA, except X-carriage and extruder parts are in ABS due to some heat issues.. No fans yet, even Nozzle does not need one...stepper motor gets warmer than nozzle-holder.... To do:
    Recode Marlin to use a ST board with color grahis and touch screen
    adjustable printbed, maybe a servo-driven nozzle
    maybe heated printbed
    new X-carriage (to get some more cm)
    Bowden extruder (lighter X carriage for more speed)
    refine all other parts to look "nicer"
    optical endstops
    .... My testfiles for adjusting are included Work is to be continued, if you are interested ...email me!

author: regolo62

description.text:
This is a direct adaptation of Lawsy's excellent Mk5 Jigsaw Replacement for the Solidoodle to make it compatible with a bowden system.  
In designing this I specifically ensured a good fit with the E3D hot-end. It should, in theory, work with the Solidoodle standard hot-end (or any other that fits in Lawsy's Mk5) but I've only tested it with the E3D.

Print with a good number of walls and high infill for strength. Drill out the bowden hole tube with a 4mm bit, just to be sure.  
Press two M4 nuts into the hex-nut-shaped holes over the top of the hot-end mount.   
Screw your bowden tube into the nuts. Drill out the interior of the bowden tube, where it goes through the nuts, with a 2mm drill to minimize friction.  
Insert the hot-end retaining arm (found in Lawsy's Mk5 thing) and screw an M3 bolt through to form the pivot. I used a longer bolt than is strictly necessary in order to form a connection point to use as a stress-break for my hot-end cables.  
Pop a blank accessory mount (also found in Lawsy's Mk5 thing) to provide extra force on the retaining arm.  
When it's all tested and you're sure you like it, superglue the M4 nuts into place for extra strength.

comments.text: Hi, looks great, how are you fastening it to the printer carriage? I was hoping that a mount could be made to lift the e3d hotend up so not to loose the height?
comments.author: Staffordknott

comments.text: It connects to the printer carriage the same way the original mount, and Lawsy's Mk5 mount, does - with the two bolts you can see just above the E3D's heat break in the photo above.

This is a chassis attached spool support. It uses some M8 rods you can have around. It is customizable in height, but the horizontal rod should be 125mm due to the dimensions of the printer chassis window. You will need tree chassis clips, one cross union and two M8 nut holders. Two M3 nut/bolt for each clip, 4xM8 nuts and a bit of your time. I use this to attach the spool on the left side window of the chassis of the printer (near the bowden extruder). Simple setup and mounting allowing a wide variety of spool dimensions. I am thinking on a mini-spool design at this moment to keep small the whole thing. A custom roller could be designed with a inner diameter of 9mm and length and external diameter according to your spool specs. Easy to design with a pair or cylinders. You can also use things like these:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:28907
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:372498
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1550861

Printing intructions: No support required. Use at least 30% infill and 4 perimeters.
